}"}],["code",{"code":"// Constraints on inputs describe preconditions...
operation calculateCreditRisk(Money(currency = 'GBP')) : CreditRisk

// ...which others can then help satisfy:
operation convertCurrency(source : Money, target : Currency) : Money( from source,  currency = target )","language":"taxi"}]],"markups":[["a",["href","https://github.com/springfox/springfox"]],["a",["href","https://vyne.co"]],["strong"],["a",["href","https://martinfowler.com/bliki/UbiquitousLanguage.html"]],["a",["href","https://github.com/Kotlin/KEEP/blob/3490e847fe51aa6deb869654029a5a514638700e/proposals/kotlin-contracts.md"]],["a",["href","https://spectrum.chat/taxi"]]],"sections":[[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"I was asked recently about the limitations of Swagger et al that had encouraged me to write Taxi."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"I think it’s a great question, and one that warrants a detailed answer. Both Swagger & RAML are obvious influences into the design of Taxi. I’ve been a big proponent, heavy user, & "],[0,[0],1,"OSS contributor"],[0,[],0," around Swagger for a number of years. They’re great tools, and I having a huge respect for them."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"However, there are limitations that I’d hit which frustrated me as user of Swagger, and there are things I was trying to achieve when building "],[0,[1],1,"Vyne"],[0,[],0," that just weren’t possible with current tooling."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"It’s worth mentioning that Swagger & RAML are both mature tools, whereas Taxi is sitting at v0.1. So, some of the goals outlined here indicate where we’re going, rather than where we are today."]]],[1,"h2",[[0,[],0,"Read & Writeability"]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Software is first & foremost a communication & storytelling medium. Good code is always measured by how well other "],[0,[2],1,"people -"],[0,[],0," not machines — are able to understand it."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Whether that’s through self documenting code, "],[0,[3],1,"ubiquitous language"],[0,[],0,", documentation hubs, BDD test suites, etc. Whatever techniques you choose to employ, the verdict is clear — The ability to capture, share and replay ideas between colleagues is a key factor in successful projects."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Swagger & RAML aren’t good communication formats for people — they’re simply too verbose. It’s a symptom of electing JSON & YAML as their languages — the content of the message gets lost in the noise of the syntax."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Look at these two snippets, both which communicate the same concept:"]]],[10,0],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Through brevity, Taxi becomes more writable by hand — which, it turns out, is a key facet for promoting readability, and encourages using Taxi to exchange ideas."]]],[1,"h3",[[0,[],0,"Types as a documentation tool"]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Taxi also has microtypes as a first class concept — aliasing primitives with more descriptive names. This promotes embedding the UbiquitousLanguage directly within the DSL, and the language as a first class citizen within the type system."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Consider the same example, this time with Microtypes added in:"]]],[10,1],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"By leveraging microtypes, the rest of our API documentation becomes much clearer too:"]]],[10,2],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Note that as Taxi is a documentation tool, (not a run-time), often we can omit parameter names in operations entirely, and the result is actually "],[0,[2],1,"more"],[0,[],0," readable."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"It also has the benefit that tooling can now make smarter choices around what to provide to the "],[0,[],0,"deletePet()"],[0,[],0," operation — not just any old "],[0,[],0,"Int"],[0,[],0," will do, it needs to be a "],[0,[],0,"PetId"],[0,[],0,"."]]],[1,"h2",[[0,[],0,"Extensibility"]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"API documentation exists to help consumers integrate. However, integration is a two-party party, and Swagger ignores one of those parties."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Swagger provides no way for consumers of an API to take the spec, and mix-in consumer specific information."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"For example, dumping an object straight to a DB, using JPA — a fairly common task. Given our models are generated from the Swagger spec, it’d be nice as consumer to simply mix-in the annotations for JPA, and be done with it."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Sometimes, Swagger models are a boundary concern, and consumers will convert the inbound object to a type specific to the domain. When that adds value, it’s a sensible pattern to apply. However, if your domain model and the swagger type are the same, then that’s just pure duplication, without merit."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Taxi supports type extensions to fulfil this need, allowing consumers to mix in definitions that are meaningful to them:"]]],[10,3],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"The compiler / generator API is designed to allow plugins, so consumers can connect a JPA specific annotation processor, and bosh — JPA annotations on your generated model. Lovely."]]],[1,"h2",[[0,[],0,"Describing behaviour, not just existence."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Swagger and RAML describe the "],[0,[2],1,"existence"],[0,[],0," of operations— the address you can find a service at, and broadly what parameters you need to pass."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Taxi aims to go beyond, and describe the "],[0,[2],1,"purpose"],[0,[],0," of the operation — what happens when you call an operation, and what constraints must you satisfy before doing so."]]],[10,4],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"This provides a model that tooling — such as "],[0,[1],1,"Vyne"],[0,[],0," — can use to understand how & when to call services, and how to chain services together to achieve goals."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"The contract DSL is one of the most interesting aspects of Taxi, but it’s also fairly early in it’s implementation — I expect to see this evolve significantly over the coming months. I’m also watching with a keen eye how others in similar spaces are tackling the issue — Kotlin’s new "],[0,[4],1,"Contracts DSL "],[0,[],0,"is really interesting."]]],[1,"h2",[[0,[],0,"Summary"]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Taxi is just getting going, but I think it offers real strengths over Swagger & RAML."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Strong interoperability with the existing tools is a design goal of Taxi. Ultimately, Taxi should exist as a superset of what’s expressible with Swagger."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Now’s a great time to provide feedback and input into the language as it evolves, to make sure we’re building a first-class DSL for describing API’s. We’ve just created our community over on Spectrum, so "],[0,[5],1,"stop by and join the conversation"],[0,[],0,"."],[0,[],0,"
